ity measure on `Ω`.\n\nNext, we define the Bernoulli distribution on a set `u` with parameter `p`:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n```\n\nThis defines the Bernoulli distribution on the set `u` with parameter `p`. The construction uses `infinitePi` to create a product measure. The key idea is that for each index `i`, we include it in the set with probability `p` if `i ∈ u`, and with probability `1-p` if `i ∉ u`. The `comap` is used to lift this distribution to the space of all subsets of `ι`.\n\nWe continue with the definition:\n\n```tactics\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n```\n\nThis provides a convenient notation `Ber(u, p)` for `bernoulliOn u p`. The `@[inherit_doc]` allows us to reuse the documentation from the definition of `bernoulliOn`.\n\nNext, we show that `Ber(u, p)` is indeed a probability measure:\n\n```tactics\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n```\n\nThis proves that `Ber(u, p)` is a probability measure. The proof uses the fact that `infinitePi` produces a probability measure, and then shows that the `comap` preserves this property.\n\nWe continue with some auxiliary lemmas:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n```\n\nThis lemma provides an alternative characterization of `bernolliOn u p` as a map of the `infinitePi