`-Bernoulli on `u` if and only if `Y` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`. This follows directly from the fact that having a certain distribution is preserved under equality in probability.\n\nFinally, we get to the main theorem:\n\n```tactics\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nThis is the main theorem. It states that if `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u` with respect to `P`, then the indicator functions `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are identically distributed with respect to `P`. \n\nTo prove this, we need to show that for any measurable set `A`, `P( {ω | i ∈ X ω} ∩ A ) = P( {ω | j ∈ X ω} ∩ A )`.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nThe proof is incomplete; we need to fill in the `map_eq` part of the `IdentDistrib` definition. Let's think about how to prove the equality of the maps.\n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we know that `P(X ω ⊆ u) = 1` for all `ω` (almost surely), and `P(i ∈ X ω) = p` for all `i ∈ u`. The key insight is that `i` and `j` are both elements of `u`, so their presence in `X ω` should have the same probability `p`.\n\nTo show the equality of the maps, we need to show that for any measurable set `A`, the sets `{ω | i ∈ X ω} ∩ A` and `{ω | j ∈ X ω} ∩ A` have the same measure.\n\nOne approach is to show that the functions `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are equal in distribution. Since `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, the distribution of `X` is the same as the product of independent Bernoulli trials with success probability `p` for each element in `u`.\n\nFor any `ω`, `i ∈ X ω` is an indicator variable that is `1` with probability `p` and `0` with probability `1-p`. Similarly for `j ∈ X ω`. Since `i, j ∈ u`, these have the same distribution. Therefore, the functions `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are identically distributed.\n\nTo complete the proof in Lean, we need to show that for any measurable set `A`, `P( {ω | i ∈ X ω} ∩ A ) = P( {ω | j ∈ X ω} ∩ A )`.\n\nWe can use the fact that `IsBernoulliOn X u p P` means `X` has the distribution `Ber(u, p)`. So `P(X = S) = Ber(u, p)(S)` for any measurable set `S`.\n\nLet's compute `P( {ω | i ∈ X ω} ∩ A )`:\n`P( {ω | i ∈ X ω} ∩ A ) = P( {ω ∈ A | i ∈ X ω} )`\nUsing the distribution of `X`, this is equal to `P( {ω ∈ A | i ∈ X ω} )`.\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, `P(i ∈ X ω) = p` for all `ω` where `P` is defined.\nSo `P( {ω ∈ A | i ∈ X ω} ) = P( {ω ∈ A | Bernoulli trial with success probability p} )`.\n\nSimilarly for `j ∈ X ω`.\nSince `i, j ∈ u`, the distribution of `i ∈ X ω` is the same as the distribution of `j ∈ X ω`.\nTherefore, `P( {ω ∈ A | i ∈ X ω} ) = P( {ω ∈ A | j ∈ X ω} )`.\n\nIn Lean, we can prove this using the properties of `IsBernoulliOn` and the fact that the distribution is the same.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n```\n\nWe need to import the necessary libraries for working with probability distributions and identically distributed random variables.\n\nNow, let's define the Bernoulli distribution on a set:\n\n```tactics\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n```\n\nWe're setting up the necessary variables and types. `ι` is the type of indices, `Ω` is the type of outcomes, `m` is the measurable space structure on `Ω`, `X` and `Y` are random variables (functions from `Ω` to sets of indices), `s` and `u` are sets of indices, `i` and `j` are specific indices, `p` and `q` are probability values, and `P` is the probability measure on `Ω`.\n\nNext, we define the Bernoulli distribution on a set `u` with parameter `p`:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n```\n\nThis defines the Bernoulli distribution on the set `u` with parameter `p`. The construction uses `infinitePi` to create a product measure. The key idea is that for each index `i`, we include it in the set with probability `p` if `i ∈ u`, and with probability `1-p` if `i ∉ u`. The `comap` is used to lift this distribution to the space of all subsets of `ι`.\n\nWe continue with the definition:\n\n```tactics\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n```\n\nThis provides a convenient notation `Ber(u, p)` for `bernoulliOn u p`. The `@[inherit_doc]` allows us to reuse the documentation from the definition of `bernoulliOn`.\n\nNext, we show that `Ber(u, p)` is indeed a probability measure:\n\n```tactics\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n```\n\nThis proves that `Ber(u, p)` is a probability measure. The proof uses the fact that `infinitePi` produces a probability measure, and then shows that the `comap` preserves this property.\n\nWe continue with some auxiliary lemmas:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n```\n\nThis lemma provides an alternative characterization of `bernolliOn u p` as a map of the `infinitePi` measure. The `comap_symm` lemma connects the `comap` operation with the `map` operation on the measurable space side.\n\nNext:\n\n```tactics\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n```\n\nThis lemma shows how `Ber(u, p)` acts on sets `S` that are subsets of the power set of `ι`. It connects the definition of `Ber(u, p)` with how it applies to sets of sets.\n\nSimilarly:\n\n```tactics\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n```\n\nThis provides another way to compute `Ber(u, p) S` using the preimage of `S` under the characteristic function of the sets.\n\nNext, we have some specific cases:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n```\n\nWhen `p = 0`, the Bernoulli distribution `Ber(u, 0)` is a Dirac delta measure at the empty set. This is because each element `i ∈ u` is included with probability 0. The proof uses the alternative characterization of `bernolliOn u 0` provided by `bernoulliOn_eq_map`.\n\nSimilarly:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n```\n\nWhen `p = 1`, the Bernoulli distribution `Ber(u, 1)` is a Dirac delta measure at the set `u`. This is because each element `i ∈ u` is included with probability 1. The proof uses the alternative characterization.\n\nNow we get to the core of the problem:\n\n```tactics\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.compl_setOf, Set.diff_eq_compl_inter, Set.inter_comm]\n```\n\nThis lemma calculates the measure of a singleton set `{s}` under `Ber(u, p)`. It shows that this measure is equal to `p^|s| * (1-p)^|u \\ s|`, which is the probability of getting exactly the set `s` when including each element of `u` with probability `p`.\n\nFinally, we reach the theorem statement:\n\n```tactics\n/-! ### Bernoulli random variables -/\n\nvariable (X u p P) in\n/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is\nthe product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/\nabbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P\n```\n\nThis defines what it means for a random variable `X` to be `p`-Bernoulli on a set `u` with respect to a probability measure `P`: it means that `X` has the distribution `Ber(u, p)`.\n\nThe key lemma is:\n\n```tactics\nlemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=\n  hasLaw_congr hXY\n```\n\nThis lemma states that if two random variables `X` and `Y` are equal almost surely with respect to `P` (i.e., `X =ᵐ[P] Y`), then `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u` if and only if `Y` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`. This follows directly from the fact that having a certain distribution is preserved under equality in probability.\n\nFinally, we get to the main theorem:\n\n```tactics\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun",
      "Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nsection Countable\nvariable [Countable ι]\n\n-- TODO: Does this hold if `ι` isn't countable? Note: the current proof only needs `u` cocountable,\n-- but we don't bother doing this minigeneralisation.\nlemma bernoulliOn_ae_subset : ∀ᵐ s ∂Ber(u, p), s ⊆ u := by\n  classical\n  change _ = _\n  simp only [Set.compl_setOf, Set.not_subset_iff_exists_mem_notMem, Set.setOf_exists, Set.setOf_and,\n    measure_iUnion_null_iff]\n  rintro a\n  by_cases ha : a ∈ u\n  · simp [*]\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) ({s | a ∈ s} ∩ {s | a ∉ u})\n    _ = Ber(u, p) {s | a ∈ s} := by simp [ha]\n    _ = infinitePi (fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n            (cylinder {a} {fun _ ↦ True}) := by\n      rw [bernoulliOn_apply']\n      congr!\n      ext\n      simp [funext_iff]\n    _ = 0 := by simp [infinitePi_cylinder _ (.singleton _), ha]\n\nend Countable\n\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.compl_setOf, Set.diff_eq_compl_inter, Set.inter_comm]\n\n/-! ### Bernoulli random variables -/\n\nvariable (X u p P) in\n/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is\nthe product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/\nabbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P\n\nlemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=\n  hasLaw_congr hXY\n\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nNow, we need to replace the `sorry` with a valid proof.\n\nWe need to show that the maps `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are equal. To do this, we can show that they have the same distribution.\n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, the distribution of `X` is `Ber(u, p)`. The map `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is the indicator function `1_{i ∈ X ω}`. The distribution of this is `p` because `i ∈ u`.\n\nSimilarly for `j`. So both maps have the distribution `p` on `1` and `1-p` on `0`.\n\nTo prove the equality of the maps, we need to show that for all measurable sets `A` in `unitInterval`, the probabilities are equal.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nsection Countable\nvariable [Countable ι]\n\n-- TODO: Does this hold if `ι` isn't countable? Note: the current proof only needs `u` cocountable,\n-- but we don't bother doing this minigeneralisation.\nlemma bernoulliOn_ae_subset : ∀ᵐ s ∂Ber(u, p), s ⊆ u := by\n  classical\n  change _ = _\n  simp only [Set.compl_setOf, Set.not_subset_iff_exists_mem_notMem, Set.setOf_exists, Set.setOf_and,\n    measure_iUnion_null_iff]\n  rintro a\n  by_cases ha : a ∈ u\n  · simp [*]\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) ({s | a ∈ s} ∩ {s | a ∉ u})\n    _ = Ber(u, p) {s | a ∈ s} := by simp [ha]\n    _ = infinitePi (fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n            (cylinder {a} {fun _ ↦ True}) := by\n      rw [bernoulliOn_apply']\n      congr!\n      ext\n      simp [funext_iff]\n    _ = 0 := by simp [infinitePi_cylinder _ (.singleton _), ha]\n\nend Countable\n\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.co