      "cs\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nsection Countable\nvariable [Countable ι]\n\n-- TODO: Does this hold if `ι` isn't countable? Note: the current proof only needs `u` cocountable,\n-- but we don't bother doing this minigeneralisation.\nlemma bernoulliOn_ae_subset : ∀ᵐ s ∂Ber(u, p), s ⊆ u := by\n  classical\n  change _ = _\n  simp only [Set.compl_setOf, Set.not_subset_iff_exists_mem_notMem, Set.setOf_exists, Set.setOf_and,\n    measure_iUnion_null_iff]\n  rintro a\n  by_cases ha : a ∈ u\n  · simp [*]\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) ({s | a ∈ s} ∩ {s | a ∉ u})\n    _ = Ber(u, p) {s | a ∈ s} := by simp [ha]\n    _ = infinitePi (fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n            (cylinder {a} {fun _ ↦ True}) := by\n      rw [bernoulliOn_apply']\n      congr!\n      ext\n      simp [funext_iff]\n    _ = 0 := by simp [infinitePi_cylinder _ (.singleton _), ha]\n\nend Countable\n\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.compl_setOf, Set.diff_eq_compl_inter, Set.inter_comm]\n\n/-! ### Bernoulli random variables -/\n\nvariable (X u p P) in\n/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is\nthe product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/\nabbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P\n\nlemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=\n  hasLaw_congr hXY\n\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove that `map (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P`. \n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we have `HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P`. The key insight is that `Ber(u, p)` is a product measure, and in a product measure, the coordinates are independent. Therefore, the inclusion of `i` and `j` into the set `X ω` are independent Bernoulli trials with parameter `p`. Hence, the random variables `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are both Bernoulli with parameter `p`, and thus they are identically distributed.\n\nTo show this, we need to prove that for any measurable set `A`, the probability of `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` being in `A` is equal to the probability of `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` being in `A`. \n\nLet's prove this equality:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nsection Countable\nvariable [Countable ι]\n\n-- TODO: Does this hold if `ι` isn't countable? Note: the current proof only needs `u` cocountable,\n-- but we don't bother doing this minigeneralisation.\nlemma bernoulliOn_ae_subset : ∀ᵐ s ∂Ber(u, p), s ⊆ u := by\n  classical\n  change _ = _\n  simp only [Set.compl_setOf, Set.not_subset_iff_exists_mem_notMem, Set.setOf_exists, Set.setOf_and,\n    measure_iUnion_null_iff]\n  rintro a\n  by_cases ha : a ∈ u\n  · simp [*]\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) ({s | a ∈ s} ∩ {s | a ∉ u})\n    _ = Ber(u, p) {s | a ∈ s} := by simp [ha]\n    _ = infinitePi (fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n            (cylinder {a} {fun _ ↦ True}) := by\n      rw [bernoulliOn_apply']\n      congr!\n      ext\n      simp [funext_iff]\n    _ = 0 := by simp [infinitePi_cylinder _ (.singleton _), ha]\n\nend Countable\n\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.compl_setOf, Set.diff_eq_compl_inter, Set.inter_comm]\n\n/-! ### Bernoulli random variables -/\n\nvariable (X u p P) in\n/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is\nthe product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/\nabbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P\n\nlemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=\n  hasLaw_congr hXY\n\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nTo prove `map_eq`, we need to show that the pushforward measures of `P` under the two functions are equal. \n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we have `HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P`. The key insight is that `Ber(u, p)` is a product measure, and in a product measure, the coordinates are independent. Therefore, the inclusion of `i` and `j` into the set `X ω` are independent Bernoulli trials with success probability `p`. Hence, the random variables `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are both Bernoulli with parameter `p`, and thus they are identically distributed.\n\nTo show this, we need to prove that for any measurable set `A`, the probability of `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` being in `A` is equal to the probability of `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` being in `A`.\n\nLet's prove this equality:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈ s) <| infinitePi fun i ↦\n    toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False\n\n@[inherit_doc] scoped notation \"Ber(\" u \", \" p \")\" => bernoulliOn u p\n\ninstance : IsProbabilityMeasure Ber(u, p) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.isProbabilityMeasure_comap <| .of_forall fun P ↦\n    ⟨{a | P a}, rfl⟩\n\nvariable (u p) in\nlemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :\n    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})\n      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=\n  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..\n\nlemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :\n    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by\n  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_zero : Ber(u, 0) = dirac ∅ := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nvariable (u) in\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_one : Ber(u, 1) = dirac u := by simp [bernoulliOn_eq_map]\n\nsection Countable\nvariable [Countable ι]\n\n-- TODO: Does this hold if `ι` isn't countable? Note: the current proof only needs `u` cocountable,\n-- but we don't bother doing this minigeneralisation.\nlemma bernoulliOn_ae_subset : ∀ᵐ s ∂Ber(u, p), s ⊆ u := by\n  classical\n  change _ = _\n  simp only [Set.compl_setOf, Set.not_subset_iff_exists_mem_notMem, Set.setOf_exists, Set.setOf_and,\n    measure_iUnion_null_iff]\n  rintro a\n  by_cases ha : a ∈ u\n  · simp [*]\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) ({s | a ∈ s} ∩ {s | a ∉ u})\n    _ = Ber(u, p) {s | a ∈ s} := by simp [ha]\n    _ = infinitePi (fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)\n            (cylinder {a} {fun _ ↦ True}) := by\n      rw [bernoulliOn_apply']\n      congr!\n      ext\n      simp [funext_iff]\n    _ = 0 := by simp [infinitePi_cylinder _ (.singleton _), ha]\n\nend Countable\n\nvariable (u p) in\n-- TODO: Generalise to countable `ι` and finite `u`. See the TODO on `infinitePi_pi`.\n@[simp] lemma bernoulliOn_singleton [Finite ι] (hsu : s ⊆ u) :\n    Ber(u, p) {s} = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (u \\ s).ncard := by\n  classical\n  cases nonempty_fintype ι\n  lift u to Finset ι using Set.toFinite _\n  calc\n    Ber(u, p) {s}\n    _ = ∏ i, ((if i ∈ u ↔ i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else 0) +\n          if i ∈ s then 0 else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      simp [bernoulliOn_apply, Set.image_singleton, Set.indicator]\n      simp [ENNReal.smul_def]\n    _ = ∏ i ∈ u, (if i ∈ s then (toNNReal p : ENNReal) else (toNNReal (σ p) : ENNReal)) := by\n      rw [← Finset.prod_subset u.subset_univ (by\n        simpa +contextual [ite_add_ite, ← ENNReal.coe_add] using fun _ ↦ mt (@hsu _))]\n      simp +contextual [ite_add_ite]\n    _ = toNNReal p ^ s.ncard * toNNReal (σ p) ^ (↑u \\ s).ncard := by\n      simp [Finset.prod_ite, ← Set.ncard_coe_finset, Set.setOf_and,\n        Set.inter_eq_right.2 hsu, ← Set.compl_setOf, Set.diff_eq_compl_inter, Set.inter_comm]\n\n/-! ### Bernoulli random variables -/\n\nvariable (X u p P) in\n/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is\nthe product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/\nabbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P\n\nlemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=\n  hasLaw_congr hXY\n\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove that `map (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P`. \n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we have `HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P`. The key insight is that `Ber(u, p)` is a product measure, and in a product measure, the coordinates are independent. Therefore, the inclusion of `i` and `j` into the set `X ω` are independent Bernoulli trials with success probability `p`. Hence, the random variables `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are both Bernoulli with parameter `p`, and thus they are identically distributed.\n\nTo show this, we need to prove that for any measurable set `A`, the probability of `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` being in `A` is equal to the probability of `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` being in `A`.\n\nLet's prove this equality:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.HasLaw\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n\n/-!\n# Bernoulli random variables\n\nThis file defines the binomial random distribution on a set. For a set `u : Set ι` and `p` between\n`0` and `1`, this is the measure on `Set ι` such that each `i ∈ u` belongs to the random set with\nprobability `p`, and each `i ∉ u` doesn't belong to it.\n\n## Notation\n\n`Ber(u, p)` is the product of `p`-Bernoulli distributions on `u`.\n\n## TODO\n\nAdd the characteristic predicate for a random variable to follow the Bernoulli distribution.\n-/\n\nopen MeasureTheory Measure unitInterval\nopen scoped Finset\n\nnamespace ProbabilityTheory\nvariable {ι Ω : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Ω} {X Y : Ω → Set ι} {s u : Set ι} {i j : ι} {p q : I}\n  {P : Measure Ω}\n\nvariable (u p) in\n/-- The binomial distribution with parameter `p` on the set `u : Set V` is the measure on `Set V`\nsuch that each element of `u` is taken with probability `p`, and the elements outside of `u` are\nnever taken. -/\nnoncomputable def bernoulliOn : Measure (Set ι) :=\n  .comap (fun s i ↦ i ∈",
      "\nlemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :\n    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where\n  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop\n  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop\n  map_eq := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove the `map_eq` part. This requires showing that for any measurable set `A` in the codomain of the first function, the probability that `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is in `A` is equal to the probability that `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` is in `A`.\n\nLet's think about how to approach this. For any set `A`, we need to show:\n`P({ω | i ∈ X ω} ∈ A) = P({ω | j ∈ X ω} ∈ A)`\n\nThis is equivalent to showing that the sets `{ω | i ∈ X ω}` and `{ω | j ∈ X ω}` have the same distribution. Let's denote these sets as `S_i` and `S_j`.\n\nWe need to show `P(S_i ∈ A) = P(S_j ∈ A)` for all `A`.\n\nLet's consider the structure of the proof. We need to show that these sets are equal in distribution. Since `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we know that `P(i ∈ X) = p` and `P(j ∈ X) = p` (since `i, j ∈ u`).\n\nTo show that `S_i` and `S_j` are identically distributed, we can use the fact that they have the same distribution. The set `S_i` is the preimage of `True` under the map `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω`. Similarly, `S_j` is the preimage of `True` under `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω`.\n\nSince `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, the probability that `i ∈ X` is `p`, so `P(S_i) = p`. Similarly, `P(S_j) = p`. \n\nFor arbitrary sets `A`, we need to show that `P(S_i ∈ A) = P(S_j ∈ A)`. Let's think about this. If `A` is a set in the codomain, then `S_i ∈ A` means that `i ∈ X` is true. Similarly, `S_j ∈ A` means `j ∈ X` is true. So we need to show that `P(i ∈ X) = P(j ∈ X)`, which we already know is true because `P(i ∈ X) = p` and `P(j ∈ X) = p`.\n\nWait, this is not correct. Let's think more carefully. The statement `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is a function from `Ω` to `Set ι` (or rather, to `Finset ι` in the context of the code, but the important part is the underlying set). The map `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is a function from `Ω` to `Bool` (true/false). So the statement `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is a boolean-valued function.\n\nThe lemma `IdentDistrib` is about the equality of the measures pushed forward by these functions. So we need to show that the probability measure `P` pushed forward by `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is equal to the probability measure `P` pushed forward by `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω`.\n\nIn other words, we need to show that for any set `A` in the codomain (which is `Bool`), the probability that `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is in `A` is equal to the probability that `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` is in `A`.\n\nLet's think of `A` as a subset of `Bool`. Then `S_i ∈ A` means that `i ∈ X` is true. Similarly, `S_j ∈ A` means `j ∈ X` is true. So we need to show that `P(i ∈ X) = P(j ∈ X)`, which we know is true because both are equal to `p`.\n\nSo, for any set `A`, we need to show that `P(i ∈ X ∈ A) = P(j ∈ X ∈ A)`. \n\nLet's write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 : (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) = (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) := by\n  funext ω\n```\n\nNow we need to show that for any `ω`, `i ∈ X ω` is equivalent to `j ∈ X ω`. This is not true in general, so we must be misunderstanding something. Let's re-read the problem.\n\nWait, we need to show that the maps `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` are identically distributed, not necessarily equal. So we need to show that they have the same distribution.\n\nLet's think about the distribution of these maps. For any `ω`, `i ∈ X ω` is true with probability `p` (since `i ∈ u`), and `j ∈ X ω` is true with probability `p` (since `j ∈ u`). The events `i ∈ X ω` and `j ∈ X ω` are independent with the same distribution. \n\nTo show that the maps are identically distributed, we need to show that for any set `A` in the codomain, the probability that `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is in `A` is equal to the probability that `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` is in `A`.\n\nLet's think of `A` as a subset of the codomain. If `A` is the set `{True}`, then `P(i ∈ X) = p` and `P(j ∈ X) = p`, so they are equal. If `A` is the set `{False}`, then `P(i ∉ X) = 1 - p` and `P(j ∉ X) = 1 - p`, so they are equal. For arbitrary sets `A`, we need to show that `P(i ∈ X ∈ A) = P(j ∈ X ∈ A)`.\n\nTo show this in Lean, we need to use the definition of identically distributed. Let's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : ∀ ω, P (fun ω_1 ↦ i ∈ X ω_1) = P (fun ω_1 ↦ j ∈ X ω_1) := by\n  intro ω\n```\n\nWait, this is not the right approach. We need to show that the pushforward measures are equal. Let's use the definition of identically distributed.\n\nFrom the definition of `IdentDistrib`:\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\n```\n\nThe definition of `IdentDistrib` is:\n```tactics\nstructure IdentDistrib (f g : Ω → α) (μ ν : Measure Ω) : Prop where\n  aemeasurable_fst : Aemeasurable f μ\n  aemeasurable_snd : Aemeasurable g ν\n  map_eq : map f μ = map g ν\n```\n\nSo we need to show that `map (fun ω => i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun ω => j ∈ X ω) P`.\n\nTo show this, we need to prove that for any set `A` in the codomain, `P({ω | fun ω_1 ↦ i ∈ X ω_1 ∈ A}) = P({ω | fun ω_1 ↦ j ∈ X ω_1 ∈ A})`.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.IdentDistrib\nimport Mathlib.Probability.ProductMeasure\n```\n\nNow we need to show that the pushforward measures are equal. Let's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : map (fun ω => i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun ω => j ∈ X ω) P := by\n```\n\nTo show this, we need to prove that for any set `A` in the codomain, the probabilities are equal:\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : ∀ A, P ((fun ω => i ∈ X ω)⁻¹' A) = P ((fun ω => j ∈ X ω)⁻¹' A) := by\n  intro A\n```\n\nNow we need to show that the preimage of `A` under `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` has the same probability as the preimage of `A` under `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω`.\n\nThe preimage of `A` under `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` is the set of all `ω` such that `i ∈ X ω` is in `A`. Similarly for `j`.\n\nLet's think of `A` as a subset of `Bool`. If `A = {True}`, then we need to show `P(i ∈ X) = P(j ∈ X)`, which is true b