Similarly, `P(j ∈ X(ω)) = p`.

Now, for any Borel set `B`, we have:
`P({ω | i ∈ X ω} ∈ B) = P(i ∈ X(ω) ∈ B)`. Since `i ∈ X(ω)` is a Bernoulli trial with parameter `p`, this is the probability that a Bernoulli(p) random variable is in `B`.

Similarly, `P(j ∈ X(ω) ∈ B) = P(Bernoulli(p) ∈ B)`. Since both are Bernoulli(p), these are equal.

