4. Since `X` has the law `Ber(u, p)`, we have `P (X ∈ B) = Ber(u, p) B` for any measurable set `B`
5. So, `P (i ∈ X ∈ A) = Ber(u, p) (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω ∈ A)`
6. And `P (j ∈ X ∈ A) = Ber(u, p) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω ∈ A)`
7. We need to show these two expressions are equal
8. Let's compute `Ber(u, p) (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω ∈ A)`
